Identification of regression towards the mean (RGTM)

  1. Measurement change with certain pattern, to the mean(observed)

  2. Condition on a certain group, variance increase with time

  3. Different from selection bias, as selection bias focuses on mean

Properities of RGTM (What changes it)

In simple case, assume different measurement are normally distributed. If more data is available, more complex model could be used to model individual variation. If measurment are normally distributed, three aspect could affect RGTM

  1. Mean of the individual.

  2. Individual How the biomarkers of individual change over time.

  3. Selection. How the data is selected. In JUPITER Trial, the selection criteria is LDLC below 130. Sometimes refered as cutoff point.

Simulation

Example

Apply no selection 

#test case, no cutoff
data<-simulation.function.v42(20000,cutoff = 1000)
data$ldlc_change<-data$ldlc12 - data$ldlcb
data$ldlc_change_m<-data$ldlc12m - data$ldlcm

data0<-data%>%filter(drug == 0)
data1<-data%>%filter(drug == 1)
hist(data0$ldlc_change)

plot(data0$ldlcb,data0$ldlc_change)

Select 90 and below 

data<-simulation.function.v42(20000,cutoff = 90)
data$ldlc_change<-data$ldlc12 - data$ldlcb
data$ldlc_change_m<-data$ldlc12m - data$ldlcm

data0<-data%>%filter(drug == 0)
data1<-data%>%filter(drug == 1)
hist(data0$ldlc_change)

plot(data0$ldlcb,data0$ldlc_change)

Apply a selection results a different behavior on LDLC

fit<-lm(data,formula = ldlc_change_m~ldlc_change+ldlcb+drug)
plot(fit$residuals)

data$ldlc_change_m_pred<-predict(fit,data)
plot(data$ldlc_change_m,data$ldlc_change_m_pred)#mean prediction works
